@Bill 
False friends are fun.

I'll try to remember what AFICIONADO means--if I made a mistake, I'd be muy embarazada!

@Bill 
Wait, isn't "amateur" the false friend in this equation? The literal translation would be "lover," but we take it to mean not professional, while a correct interpretation would be playing for the love of the game. An amateur golfer may get a nice paycheck in a pro-am tournament.

Not arguing with you, just trying to get my head around the "false friend" concept, which it fairly new to me.

@Grant 
Any native speakers of Spanish or French, please correct me, but my understanding is that in Spanish, "aficionado/a" can mean either [devotee/fan], or [non-professional/hobbyist], whereas in English it can only mean the former. Similarly, in French, "amateur/trice" can mean either of those same two, whereas in English it can only mean the second. And despite the obvious etymology, in French you wouldn't use "amateur," instead you'd use "amant/e" to refer to the person you were having the noonsie with.

Unless, of course, you're commenting on his/her prowess.

@Bill 
Honestly, it never occurred to me, until today, that ama (love) was the root of amateur. And then it was beat-me-over-the-head obvious.

And for me, AFICIONADO will always be a specific reference to bull-fighting enthusiasts, thanks to Hemingway. I'm sure there are "amateur" bull-fighters, but I'd rather not think too hard about that.

@Steve L 
