@Marco 

Forgive me if you already know this (your English is much better than my extremely limited Spanish), but you do realize that “uncle” is an idiom in American English that means “I give up?” 

I remember it from my childhood, when one kid would do something like literally twisting another child’s arm while saying, “Say ‘uncle’!”

@Marco 

Interesting that you found that to be a difficult entry. To me, it was a "gimme," I found it to be a very clever clue.  I'm thinking you're too young to know about the infamous 1980 Sugar Ray Leonard/Roberto Durán boxing match.  Sugar Ray was really beating up on Durán. Durán quit the match in the eighth round by saying, "No más," which means "no more." That's akin to the English slang word "uncle," meaning "I give up." 
I immediately knew the answer since I had watched the fight.

@Nancy Sculerati MD,

I believe I hear what you’re saying.  You’re right, knowing  that words have more than one meaning makes them tailor-made either for clues that will deliberately mislead the solver, or for answers that create those wonderful “aha” moments. The fact that the NYT crosswords do that consistently so well makes solving them a pleasant and rewarding activity for many people. 

Sounds like you’re open to seeing crosswords in a slightly different way than in the past. Please don’t be dissuaded by negative comments from trying this out. I think you might like it here.

